For KVM, you can absolutely build a VMware-like workflow with:

Part 1: Full Clone (Independent VM)
Best method:
virsh shutdown alpine1
virt-clone \
  --original alpine1 \
  --name alpine1-prod01 \
  --file /var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine1-prod01.qcow2
Start:
virsh start alpine1-prod01
Result:
Independent VM
Separate disk
Separate UUID
Separate MAC
Safe for production
Part 2: Create KVM Template (Like VMware Templates)

KVM doesn’t have native templates like VMware vSphere, but you can create golden images.

Recommended Template Workflow
Step 1: Build base VM

Install:

OS
Updates
Packages
Cloud-init or customization scripts

Example:

apk add cloud-init qemu-guest-agent
Step 2: Clean system identity
truncate -s 0 /etc/machine-id
rm -f /var/lib/dbus/machine-id
rm -f /etc/ssh/ssh_host_*
Step 3: Shutdown:
virsh shutdown alpine-template
Step 4: Mark as template

Rename:

mv alpine-template.qcow2 alpine-template-master.qcow2
Step 5: Deploy new VM from template
Full clone:
qemu-img convert -O qcow2 \
/var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine-template-master.qcow2 \
/var/lib/libvirt/images/newvm01.qcow2
Define VM:
virt-install \
  --name newvm01 \
  --memory 2048 \
  --vcpus 2 \
  --disk path=/var/lib/libvirt/images/newvm01.qcow2 \
  --import \
  --os-variant alpine \
  --network bridge=br0 \
  --noautoconsole
Alternative:
Use virt-sysprep
virt-sysprep -d alpine-template

This automatically cleans:

SSH keys
Logs
Machine IDs
Hostname
User history
